## FROZEN SOURCE — pinned artifacts (BUSL header, but not for the usual reason)

These keep the **BUSL-1.1** header — **not** because we want to restrict them, but because
**their compiled bytecode is pinned on-chain and their source is therefore frozen.**

    cell/contracts/tools/   WithdrawCreditsV1 · WithdrawCreditsV1ArtifactProbe
                            TransferCreditsV1 · TransferCreditsV1ArtifactProbe
                            AuditResultV1 · AuditCaseV1
    cell/contracts/         GenesisBootstrapTarget · TutorialDualVault · SmokeTarget
                            Gate0Target · Gate0R2Target · Gate0R2TargetFix · Gate0R3Target
                            Gate0G10Target · Gate0G10ThrowawayFix · Eip712Reference

A tool's identity is content-bound: `WithdrawCreditsV1.TOOL_ARTIFACT_HASH` is
`keccak256(runtime bytecode)`, and `toolId` derives from it. Solidity embeds a metadata hash of
the **source text** in the runtime code — so changing even a comment (an SPDX line included)
changes the bytecode, changes the artifact hash, and **breaks reproduction**: you would clone
this repo, re-derive the hash, and get a value that does not match the one the chain pinned.

That reproduction is the entire promise of this project. It outranks a licensing preference.
These files are relicensed to MIT at the next artifact **re-baseline**, when source, deployed
bytecode and published repo move as one generation. Until then the header stands, and you are
free to read, run and verify them — which is all anyone needs them for.

*(`cell/test/` and `cell/script/` also still carry BUSL headers — a test harness and deploy
scripts, nothing to "productionise". Cosmetic, binds nobody.)*

## Why it's split this way

**The core is BUSL** because it's what a funded competitor would clone wholesale to launch a
rival network. A licence-violating fork is unfundable and unauditable — no serious investor or
audit firm touches one. It's a **deterrent, not a wall**: it does not stop an anonymous
deployer, and it isn't meant to.

**The surface is MIT on purpose.** BUSL restricts *production use* — and running an organ
service (an indexer, a tier service, an FMEA watchdog, a Bob-card integrator) **is** production
use. Putting BUSL on the interfaces would tax the exact permissionless market this network
exists to create. The product is an accumulating canonical toolkit; a toolkit nobody may run is
not a toolkit.

So: **verify us, integrate with us, build on us — freely. Just don't fork the settlement core
and run it as a competing network without talking to us.**

